<keyStep id="30C01FE61609FFE6B5A1E1236FDACF42" pageId="31" pageNumber="347">
<paragraph id="8B8B07431609FFE6B5A1E1236FDACF60" blockId="31.[159,1156,516,1337]" box="[159,1155,516,540]" pageId="31" pageNumber="347">
<keyLead id="30C5A4761609FFE6B5A1E1236FDACF60" box="[159,1155,516,540]" pageId="31" pageNumber="347">
(1) Dorsum of mesosoma without projecting hairs (
<figureCitation id="130F1BC61609FFE6B7D3E1236801CF60" box="[749,856,516,540]" captionStart="Figure 16" captionStartId="32.[160,225,1657,1680]" captionTargetBox="[178,1138,142,1626]" captionTargetId="figure-1@32.[178,1138,142,1626]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="Figure 16. Monomorium key illustrations: (a) Mesosoma without hairs. (b) Mesosoma with hairs. (c) M. dichroum. (d) Head of M. dichroum. (e) Mesosoma of M. elghazalyi sp. nov. showing deeply impressed metanotal groove." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5184327" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5184327/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="347">Figure 16</figureCitation>
(a)) .......................................... 2
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8B07431609FFE6B5F9E1016FDACF42" blockId="31.[159,1156,516,1337]" box="[199,1155,550,574]" pageId="31" pageNumber="347">
<keyLead id="30C5A4761609FFE6B5F9E1016FDACF42" box="[199,1155,550,574]" pageId="31" pageNumber="347">
Dorsum of mesosoma with projecting hairs (
<figureCitation id="130F1BC61609FFE6B7FBE1016875CF42" box="[709,812,550,574]" captionStart="Figure 16" captionStartId="32.[160,225,1657,1680]" captionTargetBox="[178,1138,142,1626]" captionTargetId="figure-1@32.[178,1138,142,1626]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="Figure 16. Monomorium key illustrations: (a) Mesosoma without hairs. (b) Mesosoma with hairs. (c) M. dichroum. (d) Head of M. dichroum. (e) Mesosoma of M. elghazalyi sp. nov. showing deeply impressed metanotal groove." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5184327" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5184327/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="347">Figure 16</figureCitation>
(b))................................................. 3
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</keyStep>
<paragraph id="8B8B07431609FFE6B5A1E16E6FDACE72" blockId="31.[159,1156,516,1337]" pageId="31" pageNumber="347">
<keyStep id="30C01FE61609FFE6B5A1E16E6FDDCEC7" pageId="31" pageNumber="347">
<keyLead id="30C5A4761609FFE6B5A1E16E6FDACE72" pageId="31" pageNumber="347">
(2) Colour yellow with the area in front of eyes and gaster except first third of first gastral tergite blackish brown (
<figureCitation id="130F1BC61609FFE6B710E14B69C3CFF8" box="[558,666,620,644]" captionStart="Figure 16" captionStartId="32.[160,225,1657,1680]" captionTargetBox="[178,1138,142,1626]" captionTargetId="figure-1@32.[178,1138,142,1626]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="Figure 16. Monomorium key illustrations: (a) Mesosoma without hairs. (b) Mesosoma with hairs. (c) M. dichroum. (d) Head of M. dichroum. (e) Mesosoma of M. elghazalyi sp. nov. showing deeply impressed metanotal groove." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5184327" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5184327/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="347">Figure 16</figureCitation>
(c)); metanotal groove shallowly impressed (
<figureCitation id="130F1BC61609FFE6B5EEE1A96A65CFDA" box="[208,316,654,678]" captionStart="Figure 16" captionStartId="32.[160,225,1657,1680]" captionTargetBox="[178,1138,142,1626]" captionTargetId="figure-1@32.[178,1138,142,1626]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="Figure 16. Monomorium key illustrations: (a) Mesosoma without hairs. (b) Mesosoma with hairs. (c) M. dichroum. (d) Head of M. dichroum. (e) Mesosoma of M. elghazalyi sp. nov. showing deeply impressed metanotal groove." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5184327" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5184327/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="347">Figure 16</figureCitation>
(c)); eyes larger with seven ommatidia in the longest row (EL 0.21 × HW); cephalic surface finely and distinctly longitudinally striated (
<figureCitation id="130F1BC61609FFE6B6B8E19668ACCFB5" box="[902,1013,689,713]" captionStart="Figure 16" captionStartId="32.[160,225,1657,1680]" captionTargetBox="[178,1138,142,1626]" captionTargetId="figure-1@32.[178,1138,142,1626]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="Figure 16. Monomorium key illustrations: (a) Mesosoma without hairs. (b) Mesosoma with hairs. (c) M. dichroum. (d) Head of M. dichroum. (e) Mesosoma of M. elghazalyi sp. nov. showing deeply impressed metanotal groove." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5184327" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5184327/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="347">Figure 16</figureCitation>
(d)); sides of head straight or feebly convex; postpetiole in dorsal view about 1.7 times broader than petiole width (
<collectingCountry id="F32347D31609FFE6B495E1D16ABFCE72" box="[427,486,758,782]" name="India" pageId="31" pageNumber="347">India</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F32347D31609FFE6B4CCE1D16919CE72" box="[498,576,758,782]" name="Yemen" pageId="31" pageNumber="347">Socotra</collectingCountry>
)................................. ................................. 
<taxonomicName id="4C347CC01609FFE6B6F1E1D16A14CE4D" authority="Forel Unicolorous" authorityName="Forel Unicolorous" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Monomorium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="347" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="dichroum">
<emphasis id="B940DB511609FFE6B6F1E1D16FDACE72" bold="true" box="[975,1155,758,782]" pageId="31" pageNumber="347">
<emphasis id="B940DB511609FFE6B6F1E1D16F64CE72" bold="true" box="[975,1085,758,782]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="347">dichroum</emphasis>
Forel
</emphasis>
<paragraph id="8B8B07431609FFE6B5F9E03E6FDDCEC7" blockId="31.[159,1156,516,1337]" pageId="31" pageNumber="347">
<keyLead id="30C5A4761609FFE6B5F9E03E6FDDCEC7" pageId="31" pageNumber="347">
Unicolorous clear yellow; metanotal groove deeply impressed and broad (
<figureCitation id="130F1BC61609FFE6B126E03E6FDACE4D" box="[1048,1155,793,817]" captionStart="Figure 16" captionStartId="32.[160,225,1657,1680]" captionTargetBox="[178,1138,142,1626]" captionTargetId="figure-1@32.[178,1138,142,1626]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="Figure 16. Monomorium key illustrations: (a) Mesosoma without hairs. (b) Mesosoma with hairs. (c) M. dichroum. (d) Head of M. dichroum. (e) Mesosoma of M. elghazalyi sp. nov. showing deeply impressed metanotal groove." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5184327" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5184327/files/figure.png" pageId="31" pageNumber="347">Figure 16</figureCitation>
(e)); eyes smaller with five ommatidia in the longest row (EL 0.19 × HW); cephalic surface unsculptured smooth, and shining; lateral sides of head clearly convex; postpetiole in dorsal view about 1.2 times broader than petiole width (
<collectingCountry id="F32347D31609FFE6B119E0A66FD9CEE5" box="[1063,1152,897,921]" name="Yemen" pageId="31" pageNumber="347">Socotra</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F32347D31609FFE6B5F9E0846A54CEC7" box="[199,269,931,955]" name="Yemen" pageId="31" pageNumber="347">Yemen</collectingCountry>
)......................................................... ......................................................... 
<taxonomicName id="4C347CC01609FFE6B69BE0846F45CEC7" authority="Sharaf &amp; Fisher &amp; Collingwood &amp; Aldawood, 2017" authorityName="Sharaf &amp; Fisher &amp; Collingwood &amp; Aldawood" authorityYear="2017" box="[933,1052,931,955]" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Monomorium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="347" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="elghazalyi" status="sp. nov.">elghazalyi</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A273662A1609FFE6B11BE0846FDDCEC7" box="[1061,1156,931,955]" pageId="31" pageNumber="347" rank="species">
<emphasis id="B940DB511609FFE6B11BE0846F24CEC7" bold="true" box="[1061,1149,931,955]" pageId="31" pageNumber="347">sp. nov</emphasis>
.
</taxonomicNameLabel>
</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</keyStep>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8B07431609FFE6B5A1E0E16FDAC95F" blockId="31.[159,1156,516,1337]" pageId="31" pageNumber="347">
<keyStep id="30C01FE61609FFE6B5A1E0E16FDAC9F7" pageId="31" pageNumber="347">
<keyLead id="30C5A4761609FFE6B5A1E0E16FDAC95F" pageId="31" pageNumber="347">
(3) Pilosity abundant and clubbed; antennae with 12 segments; eyes large with 10–11 ommatidia in the longest row; mandibles sculptured (
<collectingCountry id="F32347D31609FFE6B611E0CE68D1C97D" box="[815,904,1001,1025]" name="Yemen" pageId="31" pageNumber="347">Socotra</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F32347D31609FFE6B6AAE0CE6885C97D" box="[916,988,1001,1025]" name="Yemen" pageId="31" pageNumber="347">Yemen</collectingCountry>
)........................... ............................................................................................................................... 
<taxonomicName id="4C347CC01609FFE6B6ACE72C6A4EC93A" authority="Collingwood Pilosity" authorityName="Collingwood Pilosity" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Monomorium" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="31" pageNumber="347" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nimihil">
<emphasis id="B940DB511609FFE6B6ACE72C6FDAC95F" bold="true" box="[914,1155,1035,1059]" pageId="31" pageNumber="347">
<emphasis id="B940DB511609FFE6B6ACE72C68BBC95F" bold="true" box="[914,994,1035,1059]" italics="true" pageId="31" pageNumber="347">nimihil</emphasis>
Collingwood
</emphasis>
<paragraph id="8B8B07431609FFE6B5F9E7096FDAC9F7" blockId="31.[159,1156,516,1337]" pageId="31" pageNumber="347">
<keyLead id="30C5A4761609FFE6B5F9E7096FDAC9F7" pageId="31" pageNumber="347">Pilosity few and simple; antennae with 11 segments; eyes smaller with four to six ommatidia in the longest row; mandibles unsculptured except for hair-pits, smooth and shining ............................................................................................................................................... 4</keyLead>
</paragraph>
</taxonomicName>
</keyLead>
</keyStep>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8B07431609FFE6B5A1E7B16FDAC9AD" blockId="31.[159,1156,516,1337]" pageId="31" pageNumber="347">
<keyStep id="30C01FE61609FFE6B5A1E7B16FDAC845" pageId="31" pageNumber="347">
<keyLead id="30C5A4761609FFE6B5A1E7B16FDAC9AD" pageId="31" pageNumber="347">
(4) Petiole node nearly as long as broad in dorsal view; petiole peduncle in profile without anteroventral process (
<collectingCountry id="F32347D31609FFE6B713E79E6931C9AD" box="[557,616,1209,1233]" name="India" pageId="31" pageNumber="347">India</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F32347D31609FFE6B74AE79E69A0C9AD" box="[628,761,1209,1233]" name="Bangladesh" pageId="31" pageNumber="347">Bangladesh</collectingCountry>
, 
<collectingCountry id="F32347D31609FFE6B63AE79E680CC9AD" box="[772,853,1209,1233]" name="Yemen" pageId="31" pageNumber="347">Socotra</collectingCountry>
).................... 
